> ###############################################################################
> #### Partner Choice Models — fastclogit version
> #### Author: Jesper Lindmarker
> ####
> #### Drop-in replacement for run_clogit_models.R using fastclogit.
> #### Sources the same config.R / loaders.R and produces identical output format.
> ####
> #### Usage on MONA:
> ####   1. Set SCRIPT_DIR below to match your Git/Code folder on MONA
> ####   2. Ensure fastclogit files are in the working directory (or installed):
> ####      - clogit_newton.cpp, clogit_sandwich.cpp, fastclogit.R,
> ####        fastclogit_methods.R, load_fastclogit.R
> ####   3. Run: source("run_fastclogit_models.R")
> ####   4. Output CSVs and RDS files are tagged with "_fast" to avoid overwriting
> ####
> #### What's different from run_clogit_models.R:
> ####   - clogit() replaced with fastclogit() via run_clogit_fast()
> ####   - Design matrix built column-by-column (no model.matrix / model.frame)
> ####   - Selective fst column loading (~18 of 117 columns)
> ####   - QR-based collinearity detection with dropped-column tracking
> ####   - Column scaling for continuous predictors (sd > 1, non-binary)
> ####   - Adaptive ridge regularization in Newton-Raphson (via clogit_newton.cpp)
> ####   - tidy_clogit() replaced with tidy_fastclogit_result() (same output cols)
> ####   - KHB decomposition ported to fastclogit (via khb_fastclogit.R)
> ####   - Memory: ~23 GB peak (down from ~120 GB with survival::clogit)
> ####
> #### Key memory optimizations:
> ####   1. Selective fst loading: only ~18 needed columns (saves ~40 GB)
> ####   2. Column-by-column design matrix: avoids model.matrix() copy (~30 GB)
> ####   3. Filter-only columns dropped after filtering
> ####   4. Source data freed inside run_clogit_fast() after building X
> ####   5. data.table freed after last model in main loop
> ###############################################################################
> 
> 
